@page "/overview"
<PageTitle>Overview - Saascade Docs</PageTitle>

<h1 id="overview">Overview</h1>

<div class="doc-layout">

<main class="documentation">

    <TechCard>
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="what-is-saascade">What is Saascade?</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">
                Saascade Blazor Components is a library of design-system-agnostic Razor components.
                Write your markup once and switch between Bootstrap 5, DaisyUI, Basecoat, or any custom
                theme without changing a single line of component code.
            </p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                Each component resolves its CSS class names at runtime through an IDesignSystem
                abstraction registered in the dependency injection container. Changing the active
                design system is a single line change in Program.cs.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard>
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="how-it-works">How It Works</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">
                Components inherit from a shared base class that injects the active IDesignSystem
                and calls GetComponentName, GetSpecializations, and GetStyleForComponent at render time.
            </p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                The Specialization parameter lets you pass framework-specific variant tokens — such as
                btn-primary in Bootstrap or btn-ghost in DaisyUI — without hard-coding them into your
                markup. The component passes the value through and the design system resolves it.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="bootstrap">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="overview-bootstrap">Bootstrap 5</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">Bootstrap 5 Overview</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                With Bootstrap 5, Saascade maps each component to the standard Bootstrap class names
                you already know. A Card becomes a div with the card class, a Button gets btn and any
                variant you pass through Specialization. You get full Bootstrap styling with zero
                Bootstrap-specific markup in your Razor files.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="daisyui">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="overview-daisyui">DaisyUI</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">DaisyUI Overview</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                With DaisyUI, Saascade maps components to DaisyUI's semantic Tailwind class names.
                The active theme colors, spacing, and border styles all come from DaisyUI's theme
                system, meaning your components automatically adapt when you switch DaisyUI themes.
                No Tailwind utility classes need to appear in your Razor markup.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="basecoat">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="overview-basecoat">Basecoat</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">Basecoat Overview</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                With Basecoat, Saascade composes components from utility-first Tailwind classes using
                Basecoat's curated class sets. The result is a minimal, unstyled-by-default aesthetic
                that gives you precise visual control. Basecoat is a good fit when you want the
                flexibility of raw Tailwind without writing every utility class manually.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

</main>

<TableOfContents Items="@([
    new TocItem("overview", "Overview"),
    new TocItem("what-is-saascade", "What is Saascade?", 2),
    new TocItem("how-it-works", "How It Works", 2),
    new TocItem("overview-bootstrap", "Bootstrap 5", 2),
    new TocItem("overview-daisyui", "DaisyUI", 2),
    new TocItem("overview-basecoat", "Basecoat", 2)
])" />

</div>
